06721nam a22008655i 9783110619775DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019947692  a97831106197757 a10.1515/97831106197752doi  a(DE-B1597)527570  a(OCoLC)1121054248  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0370302bisacsh04aThe French Revolution as a Moment of Respatialization /ced. by Matthias Middell, Megan Maruschke. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (VIII, 254 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDialectics of the Global ;v500tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- t1. Explaining Revolutionary Upheaval: From Internal Societal Developments to Global Processes of Respatialization -- tPart I: Expanding the Scope of the French Revolution -- t2. Why did France want Louisiana Back? -- t3. The French Revolution as a Period of Territorialization of the Colonial Empire? A Southern Indian Ocean Perspective -- t4. Black Rebels and Royal Auxiliaries Before, During, and After the French Revolution -- tPart II: The Impact of the French Revolution -- t5. The French Revolution in Indian Country: Reconsidering the Reach and Place of Atlantic Upheaval -- t6. Mobility, Circulation, Spatial Configurations, and Respatialization in the Wake of the Haitian Revolution: A View from New Granada's Shores -- t7. Islands in Turmoil: The Azores during the Atlantic Revolutionary Cycle -- t8. The Respatialization of Cypriot Insularity during the Age of Revolutions -- tPart III: The New Spatial Organization of Societies -- t9. The Reorganization of Administrative Space in France and its Colonies -- t10. (Re)spatialization and its Limits: Territory and Descent, Ideology and Pragmatism in Definitions of Citizenship -- t11. The Respatialization of Italy between French Republics and Napoleonic Domination -- t12. From Empire to Republics: The Collapse of the Spanish Monarchy and the Respatialization of America -- tAuthors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe French Revolution has primarily been understood as a national event that also had a lasting impact in Europe and in the Atlantic world. Recently, historiography has increasingly emphasized how France's overseas colonies also influenced the contours of the French Revolution. This volume examines the effects of both dimensions on the reorganization of spatial formats and spatial orders in France and in other societies. It departs from the assumption that revolutions shatter not only the political and economic old regime order at home but, in an increasingly interdependent world, also result in processes of respatialization. The French Revolution, therefore, is analysed as a key event in a global history that seeks to account for the shifting spatial organization of societies on a transregional scale.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aBourgeoisie. 4aGlobalisierung. 4aRaumgeschichte. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh  aBourgeoisie.  aGlobalization.  aSpatial History.1 aBassi, Ernesto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCovo, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrouch, Christian Ayne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFahrmeir, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiore, Laura di, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary